data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0, "Expected at least one user");
    // or with CollectionAssert:
    CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(users); // if using MSTest v3+

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));
    // or in MSTest v2:
    foreach (var u in users) Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive, $"User {u.Name} is not active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` or `CollectionAssert` methods |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == n)` | `Assert.AreEqual(n, x.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.All(...))` | Loop + `Assert.IsTrue` per item (better failure messages) |
| Collection equality | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual` / `AreEquivalent` |
| Contains check | `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` |

The main benefit: **better failure messages**. `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` tells you "expected 3, got 5" instead of just "expected true, got false".
